# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opencv-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The purpose of early image processing was to improve the quality of the image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] In image processing, the input is a low-quality image, and the output is an image with improved quality.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Common image processing includes image enhancement, restoration, encoding, and compression.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The first successful application was the American Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] They used image processing techniques such as geometric correction, gradation transformation, noise removal, etc. on the thousands of lunar photos sent back by the Space Detector Ranger 7 in 1964, taking into account the position of the Sun and the environment of the Moon.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The impact of the successful mapping of the Moon's surface map by the computer has been a success.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Later, more complex image processing was performed on the nearly 100,000 photos sent back by the spacecraft, so that the topographic map, color map and panoramic mosaic of the Moon were obtained, which achieved extraordinary results and laid a solid foundation for human landing on the Moon.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The cost of processing was fairly high, however, with the computing equipment of that era.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] That changed in the 1970s, when digital image processing proliferated as cheaper computers and dedicated hardware became available.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This led to images being processed in real-time, for some dedicated problems such as television standards conversion.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] As general-purpose computers became faster, they started to take over the role of dedicated hardware for all but the most specialized and computer-intensive operations.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] With the fast computers and signal processors available in the 2000s, digital image processing has become the most common form of image processing, and is generally used because it is not only the most versatile method, but also the cheapest.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The basis for modern image sensors is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, This led to the development of digital semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the CMOS sensor.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The charge-coupled device was invented by Willard S.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later developed by Eric Fossum's team at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] DCT compression became the basis for JPEG, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format on the Internet.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Its highly efficient DCT compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Electronic signal processing was revolutionized by the wide adoption of MOS technology in the 1970s.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] MOS integrated circuit technology was the basis for the first single-chip microprocessors and microcontrollers in the early 1970s, and then the first single-chip digital signal processor (DSP) chips in the late 1970s.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] DSP chips have since been widely used in digital image processing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) image compression algorithm has been widely implemented in DSP chips, with many companies developing DSP chips based on DCT technology.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] DCTs are widely used for encoding, decoding, video coding, audio coding, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, analog-to-digital conversion, formatting luminance and color differences, and color formats such as YUV444 and YUV411.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Digital image processing allows the use of much more complex algorithms, and hence, can offer both more sophisticated performance at simple tasks, and the implementation of methods which would be impossible by analogue means.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Digital filters are used to blur and sharpen digital images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Notice that the highpass filter shows extra edges when zero padded compared to the repeated edge padding.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] MATLAB example for spatial domain highpass filtering.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] To apply the affine matrix to an image, the image is converted to a matrix in which each entry corresponds to the pixel intensity at that location.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Then each pixel's location can be represented as a vector indicating the coordinates of that pixel in the image, [*x*, *y*], where *x* and *y* are the row and column of a pixel in the image matrix.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate to be multiplied by an affine-transformation matrix, which gives the position that the pixel value will be copied to in the output image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] However, to allow transformations that require translation transformations, 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates are needed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The third dimension is usually set to a non-zero constant, usually 1, so that the new coordinate is [*x*, *y*, 1].
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate vector to be multiplied by a 3×3 matrix, enabling translation shifts.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Thus, the third dimension, i.e., the constant 1, allows translation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Because matrix multiplication is associative, multiple affine transformations can be combined into a single affine transformation by multiplying the matrix of each individual transformation in the order that the transformations are done.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This results in a single matrix that, when applied to a point vector, gives the same result as all the individual transformations performed on the vector [*x*, *y*, 1] in sequence.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Thus, a sequence of affine transformation matrices can be reduced to a single affine transformation matrix.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] For example, 2-dimensional coordinates only permit rotation about the origin (0, 0).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] But 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates can be used to first translate any point to (0, 0), then perform the rotation, and lastly translate the origin (0, 0) back to the original point (the opposite of the first translation).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] These three affine transformations can be combined into a single matrix, thus allowing rotation around any point in the image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Mathematical morphology (MM) is a nonlinear image processing framework that analyzes shapes within images by probing local pixel neighborhoods using a small, predefined function called a structuring element.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] In the context of grayscale images, MM is especially useful for denoising through dilation and erosion—primitive operators that can be combined to build more complex filters.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Here, ${\mathcal {S}}$ defines the neighborhood of relative coordinates $(m,n)$ over which local operations are computed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The values of $B(m,n)$ bias the image during dilation and erosion.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] MM operations, such as opening and closing, are composite processes that utilize both dilation and erosion to modify the structure of an image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] These operations are particularly useful for tasks such as noise removal, shape smoothing, and object separation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] For example, applying opening to an image f with a structuring element B would first reduce small details (through erosion) and then restore the main shapes (through dilation).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] This ensures that unwanted noise is removed without significantly altering the size or shape of larger objects.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] For instance, applying closing to the same image f would fill in small gaps within objects, such as connecting breaks in thin lines or closing small holes, while ensuring that the surrounding areas are not significantly affected.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Both opening and closing can be visualized as ways of refining the structure of an image: opening simplifies and removes small, unnecessary details, while closing consolidates and connects objects to form more cohesive structures.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Digital cameras generally include specialized digital image processing hardware – either dedicated chips or added circuitry on other chips – to convert the raw data from their image sensor into a color-corrected image in a standard image file format.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Additional post-processing techniques increase edge sharpness or color saturation to create more naturally looking images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Face detection can be implemented with mathematical morphology, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), and horizontal projection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The feature-based method of face detection uses skin tone, edge detection, face shape, and features of a face (like eyes, mouth, etc.) to achieve face detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The skin tone, face shape, and all the unique elements that only the human face has can be described as features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Normally, HSV or RGB color spaces are suitable for the skin filter.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] After filtering images with skin tone, to get the face edge, morphology and DCT are used to remove noise and fill up missing skin areas.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] DCT is to avoid the object with skin-like tone.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Since human faces always have higher texture.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Sobel operator or other operators can be applied to detect face edge.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] To position human features like eyes, using the projection and finding the peak of the histogram of projection helps to get the detailed features like mouth, hair, and lip.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Image quality can be influenced by camera vibration, over-exposure, gray level distribution too centralized, and noise, etc.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] For example, the noise problem can be solved by smoothing method, while the gray level distribution problem can be improved by histogram equalization.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] In drawing, if there is some dissatisfied color, taking some color around the dissatisfied color and averaging them.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The smoothing method can be implemented with a mask and convolution.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Take the small image and mask, for instance, as below.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] The original image pixel is 1, 4, 28, 30.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] After the smoothing mask, the pixel becomes 9, 10, 9, 9, respectively.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Generally, given a gray level histogram from an image as below.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Changing the histogram to a uniform distribution from an image is usually what we call histogram equalization.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] In discrete time, the area of gray level histogram is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}H(p_{i})$ (see figure 1) while the area of uniform distribution is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}G(q_{i})$ (see figure 2).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] Moreover, based on the definition of a function, the Gray level histogram method is like finding a function f that satisfies f(p)=q.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] **Variability in image quality**: Variations in image quality and resolution, including blurry images and incomplete details, can hinder uniform processing across a database.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] **Object detection and Recognition**: Identifying and recognising objects within images, especially in complex scenarios with multiple objects and occlusions, poses a significant challenge.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] **Data annotation and labelling**: Labelling diverse and multiple images for machine recognition is crucial for further processing accuracy, as incorrect identification can lead to unrealistic results.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/digital-image-processing] **Computational resource intensity**: Accessing adequate computational resources for image processing can be challenging and costly, hindering progress without sufficient resources.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In computer vision and image processing, a **feature** is a piece of information about the content of an image; typically about whether a certain region of the image has certain properties.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features may be specific structures in the image such as points, edges or objects.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features may also be the result of a general neighborhood operation or **feature detection** applied to the image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Other examples of features are related to motion in image sequences, or to shapes defined in terms of curves or boundaries between different image regions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] More broadly a *feature* is any piece of information that is relevant for solving the computational task related to a certain application.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] This is the same sense as feature in machine learning and pattern recognition generally, though image processing has a very sophisticated collection of features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The feature concept is very general and the choice of features in a particular computer vision system may be highly dependent on the specific problem at hand.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] There is no universal or exact definition of what constitutes a feature, and the exact definition often depends on the problem or the type of application.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, a feature is typically defined as an "interesting" part of an image, and features are used as a starting point for many computer vision algorithms.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Since features are used as the starting point and main primitives for subsequent algorithms, the overall algorithm will often only be as good as its feature detector.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, the desirable property for a feature detector is *repeatability*: whether or not the same feature will be detected in two or more different images of the same scene.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Feature detection is a low-level image processing operation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] That is, it is usually performed as the first operation on an image and examines every pixel to see if there is a feature present at that pixel.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] If this is part of a larger algorithm, then the algorithm will typically only examine the image in the region of the features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] As a built-in pre-requisite to feature detection, the input image is usually smoothed by a Gaussian kernel in a scale-space representation and one or several feature images are computed, often expressed in terms of local image derivative operations.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Occasionally, when feature detection is computationally expensive and there are time constraints, a higher-level algorithm may be used to guide the feature detection stage so that only certain parts of the image are searched for features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] There are many computer vision algorithms that use feature detection as the initial step, so as a result, a very large number of feature detectors have been developed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] These vary widely in the kinds of feature detected, the computational complexity and the repeatability.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The distinction becomes relevant when the resulting detected features are relatively sparse.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Although local decisions are made, the output from a feature detection step does not need to be a binary image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The result is often represented in terms of sets of (connected or unconnected) coordinates of the image points where features have been detected, sometimes with subpixel accuracy.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] When feature extraction is done without local decision making, the result is often referred to as a *feature image*.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, a feature image can be seen as an image in the sense that it is a function of the same spatial (or temporal) variables as the original image, but where the pixel values hold information about image features instead of intensity or color.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] This means that a feature image can be processed in a similar way as an ordinary image generated by an image sensor.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Feature images are also often computed as integrated step in algorithms for feature detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In some applications, it is not sufficient to extract only one type of feature to obtain the relevant information from the image data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Instead, two or more different features are extracted, resulting in two or more feature descriptors at each image point.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] A common practice is to organize the information provided by all these descriptors as the elements of one single vector, commonly referred to as a **feature vector**.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The set of all possible feature vectors constitutes a **feature space**.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] A common example of feature vectors appears when each image point is to be classified as belonging to a specific class.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Assuming that each image point has a corresponding feature vector based on a suitable set of features, meaning that each class is well separated in the corresponding feature space, the classification of each image point can be done using standard classification method.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] , which are correlated with "nodes" that represent visual features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Another and related example occurs when neural network-based processing is applied to images.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The input data fed to the neural network is often given in terms of a feature vector from each image point, where the vector is constructed from several different features extracted from the image data.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] During a learning phase, the network can itself find which combinations of different features are useful for solving the problem at hand.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Edges are points where there is a boundary (or an edge) between two image regions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In general, an edge can be of almost arbitrary shape, and may include junctions.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In practice, edges are usually defined as sets of points in the image that have a strong gradient magnitude.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Furthermore, some common algorithms will then chain high gradient points together to form a more complete description of an edge.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] These algorithms usually place some constraints on the properties of an edge, such as shape, smoothness, and gradient value.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Locally, edges have a one-dimensional structure.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The terms corners and interest points are used somewhat interchangeably and refer to point-like features in an image, which have a local two-dimensional structure.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The name "Corner" arose since early algorithms first performed edge detection, and then analyzed the edges to find rapid changes in direction (corners).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] These algorithms were then developed so that explicit edge detection was no longer required, for instance by looking for high levels of curvature in the image gradient.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] It was then noticed that the so-called corners were also being detected on parts of the image that were not corners in the traditional sense (for instance a small bright spot on a dark background may be detected).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] These points are frequently known as interest points, but the term "corner" is used by tradition.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Blobs provide a complementary description of image structures in terms of regions, as opposed to corners that are more point-like.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, blob descriptors may often contain a preferred point (a local maximum of an operator response or a center of gravity) which means that many blob detectors may also be regarded as interest point operators.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Blob detectors can detect areas in an image that are too smooth to be detected by a corner detector.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consider shrinking an image and then performing corner detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The detector will respond to points that are sharp in the shrunk image, but may be smooth in the original image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] It is at this point that the difference between a corner detector and a blob detector becomes somewhat vague.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] To a large extent, this distinction can be remedied by including an appropriate notion of scale.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, due to their response properties to different types of image structures at different scales, the LoG and DoH blob detectors are also mentioned in the article on corner detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] For elongated objects, the notion of *ridges* is a natural tool.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] A ridge descriptor computed from a grey-level image can be seen as a generalization of a medial axis.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] From a practical viewpoint, a ridge can be thought of as a one-dimensional curve that represents an axis of symmetry, and in addition has an attribute of local ridge width associated with each ridge point.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Unfortunately, however, it is algorithmically harder to extract ridge features from general classes of grey-level images than edge-, corner- or blob features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Nevertheless, ridge descriptors are frequently used for road extraction in aerial images and for extracting blood vessels in medical images—see ridge detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The extraction of features are sometimes made over several scalings.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] One of these methods is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Once features have been detected, a local image patch around the feature can be extracted.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] This extraction may involve quite considerable amounts of image processing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The result is known as a feature descriptor or feature vector.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Among the approaches that are used to feature description, one can mention *N*-jets and local histograms (see scale-invariant feature transform for one example of a local histogram descriptor).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In addition to such attribute information, the feature detection step by itself may also provide complementary attributes, such as the edge orientation and gradient magnitude in edge detection and the polarity and the strength of the blob in blob detection.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] A specific image feature, defined in terms of a specific structure in the image data, can often be represented in different ways.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] For example, an edge can be represented as a Boolean variable in each image point that describes whether an edge is present at that point.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Alternatively, we can instead use a representation that provides a certainty measure instead of a Boolean statement of the edge's existence and combine this with information about the orientation of the edge.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Similarly, the color of a specific region can either be represented in terms of the average color (three scalars) or a color histogram (three functions).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] When a computer vision system or computer vision algorithm is designed the choice of feature representation can be a critical issue.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In some cases, a higher level of detail in the description of a feature may be necessary for solving the problem, but this comes at the cost of having to deal with more data and more demanding processing.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Below, some of the factors which are relevant for choosing a suitable representation are discussed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In this discussion, an instance of a feature representation is referred to as a *feature descriptor*, or simply *descriptor*.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Two examples of image features are local edge orientation and local velocity in an image sequence.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In the case of orientation, the value of this feature may be more or less undefined if more than one edge are present in the corresponding neighborhood.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Local velocity is undefined if the corresponding image region does not contain any spatial variation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] As a consequence of this observation, it may be relevant to use a feature representation that includes a measure of certainty or confidence related to the statement about the feature value.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Otherwise, it is a typical situation that the same descriptor is used to represent feature values of low certainty and feature values close to zero, with a resulting ambiguity in the interpretation of this descriptor.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Depending on the application, such an ambiguity may or may not be acceptable.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In particular, if a featured image will be used in subsequent processing, it may be a good idea to employ a feature representation that includes information about certainty or confidence.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] This enables a new feature descriptor to be computed from several descriptors, for example, computed at the same image point but at different scales, or from different but neighboring points, in terms of a weighted average where the weights are derived from the corresponding certainties.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In the simplest case, the corresponding computation can be implemented as a low-pass filtering of the featured image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The resulting feature image will, in general, be more stable to noise.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] In addition to having certainty measures included in the representation, the representation of the corresponding feature values may itself be suitable for an averaging operation or not.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Most feature representations can be averaged in practice, but only in certain cases can the resulting descriptor be given a correct interpretation in terms of a feature value.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Such representations are referred to as *averageable*.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] For example, if the orientation of an edge is represented in terms of an angle, this representation must have a discontinuity where the angle wraps from its maximal value to its minimal value.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Consequently, it can happen that two similar orientations are represented by angles that have a mean that does not lie close to either of the original angles and, hence, this representation is not averageable.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] There are other representations of edge orientation, such as the structure tensor, which are averageable.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Another example relates to motion, where in some cases only the normal velocity relative to some edge can be extracted.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] If two such features have been extracted and they can be assumed to refer to same true velocity, this velocity is not given as the average of the normal velocity vectors.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Hence, normal velocity vectors are not averageable.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Instead, there are other representations of motions, using matrices or tensors, that give the true velocity in terms of an average operation of the normal velocity descriptors.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] Features detected in each image can be matched across multiple images to establish *corresponding features* such as *corresponding points*.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] The algorithm is based on comparing and analyzing point correspondences between the reference image and the target image.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/feature-detection-computer-vision] If any part of the cluttered scene shares correspondences greater than the threshold, that part of the cluttered scene image is targeted and considered to include the reference object there.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] It is widely used in computer vision tasks such as image annotation, vehicle counting, activity recognition, face detection, face recognition, video object co-segmentation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] It is also used in tracking objects, for example tracking a ball during a football match, tracking movement of a cricket bat, or tracking a person in a video.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Often, the test images are sampled from a different data distribution, making the object detection task significantly more difficult.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] To address the challenges caused by the domain gap between training and test data, many unsupervised domain adaptation approaches have been proposed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] A simple and straightforward solution for reducing the domain gap is to apply an image-to-image translation approach, such as cycle-GAN.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Among other uses, cross-domain object detection is applied in autonomous driving, where models can be trained on a vast amount of video game scenes, since the labels can be generated without manual labor.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Every object class has its own special features that help in classifying the class – for example all circles are round.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Object class detection uses these special features.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] For example, when looking for circles, objects that are at a particular distance from a point (i.e. the center) are sought.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Similarly, when looking for squares, objects that are perpendicular at corners and have equal side lengths are needed.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] A similar approach is used for face identification where eyes, nose, and lips can be found and features like skin color and distance between eyes can be found.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] For object localization, true positive is often measured by the thresholded intersection over union.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] For example, if there is a traffic sign in the image, with a bounding box drawn by a human ("ground truth label"), then a neural network has detected the traffic sign (a **true positive**) at 0.5 threshold if it has drawn a bounding box whose IoU with the ground truth is above 0.5.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Otherwise, the bounding box is a **false positive**.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] If there is only a single ground truth bounding box, but multiple predictions, then the IoU of each prediction is calculated.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] The prediction with the highest IoU is a true positive if it is above threshold, else it is a false positive.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] All other predicted bounding boxes are false positives.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] If there is no prediction with an IoU above the threshold, then the ground truth label has a **false negative**.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] For simultaneous object localization and classification, a true positive is one where the class label is correct, and the bounding box has an IoU exceeding the threshold.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Simultaneous object localization and classification is benchmarked by the **mean average precision** (mAP).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] The average precision (AP) of the network for a class of objects is the area under the precision-recall curve as the confidence threshold is varied.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] The mAP is the average of AP over all classes.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] Methods for object detection generally fall into either neural network-based or non-neural approaches.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] For non-neural approaches, it becomes necessary to first define features using one of the methods below, then using a technique such as support vector machine (SVM) to do the classification.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/object-detection] On the other hand, neural techniques are able to do end-to-end object detection without specifically defining features, and are typically based on convolutional neural networks (CNN).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] Officially launched in 1999, the OpenCV project was initially an Intel Research initiative to advance CPU-intensive applications, part of a series of projects including real-time ray tracing and 3D display walls.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] The main contributors to the project included a number of optimization experts in Intel Russia, as well as Intel's Performance Library Team.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] The first alpha version of OpenCV was released to the public at the IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition in 2000, and five betas were released between 2001 and 2005.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] The first 1.0 version was released in 2006.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] A version 1.1 "pre-release" was released in October 2008.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] The second major release of the OpenCV was in October 2009.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] OpenCV 2 includes major changes to the C++ interface, aiming at easier, more type-safe patterns, new functions, and better implementations for existing ones in terms of performance (especially on multi-core systems).
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] Official releases now occur every six months and development is now done by an independent Russian team supported by commercial corporations.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] In August 2012, support for OpenCV was taken over by a non-profit foundation, OpenCV.org, which maintains a developer and user site.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] In May 2016, Intel signed an agreement to acquire Itseez, a leading developer of OpenCV.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] OpenCV is written in the programming language C++, as is its primary interface.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] There are language bindings in Python, Java, and MATLAB/Octave.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] The application programming interface (API) for these interfaces can be found in the online documentation.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] Wrapper libraries in several languages have been developed to encourage adoption by a wider audience.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] In version 3.4, JavaScript bindings for a selected subset of OpenCV functions were released as OpenCV.js, to be used for web platforms.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] If the library finds Intel's Integrated Performance Primitives on the system, it will use these proprietary optimized routines to accelerate itself.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] A Compute Unified Device Architecture (CUDA) based graphics processing unit (GPU) interface has been in progress since September 2010.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] An OpenCL-based GPU interface has been in progress since October 2012, documentation for version 2.4.13.3 can be found at docs.opencv.org.
[src:opencv-cpp-lib/opencv] An IPU may also utilise OpenCV hardware acceleration.
